I parked nearby at a metered spot on the street. It was very easy. I walked in and was immediately greeted by the associate who right away asked "have you ever been here before" I told him no and was struck by how simple and concise the menu was. He asked "would you like me to explain the menu" and he did very well.  The tables were clean, the atmosphere seemed bright and airy. The tv monitors had great slides about ingredient information. Everything looked neat and tidy.  We ordered a six pack of the baos, eight pack of the pot stickers and two sides of noodles - so we could try a variety of things. It wasn't until two or three into the boas that I noticed the paper on the bottom of the baos had the label to identify which bao was which. The ones we had were very good. The consensus among myself and my companion were that the bbq was our favorite. Everything was very flavorful. Some baos were a bit spicier than others so I would have liked to know that and saved those for last to preserve my tastebuds for the other ones. The pot stickers were very delicious. They were crispy on the outside garnished with cut scallions. I watched the worker take them out of a drawer frozen and was concerned that they would taste frozen, but was pleasantly surprised to find that they tasted fresh. The noodles were very greasy, but I hadn't realized it was because they had a sesame oil on them; which I wasn't aware of. I enjoyed them, but just wasn't expecting that since there were sauces included in the bag, I assumed they were intended to go on the noodles. Wished they would have been labeled so I knew what the sauces were and how to use them. I tasted all of them and find them tasty, the flavors were there, just had a difficult time determining what they were. The pot stickers were definitely the favorite of everything.
